Seriously though, I am a little sick of the "am I guilty if I wanted someone dead SUBCONSCIOUSLY" angle in mysteries. Enough. You aren't. Let's tackle something else. 

Also hypnosis is not a thing *cough*Kindaichi37*cough*. <--my brain thinks this is relevant but it needs too much explaining

『疑惑』is Freudian.😅 While acknowledging we owe the "subconscious" concept to him, I cordially dislike Freudian psychology so I wish it weren't that prominent in the story. Otherwise, I enjoyed the whole temporal + mental disconnect between actions (that led to killing) & motive.

『赤い部屋』is about perfect crimes & ends somewhat ambiguously (wrt whether the storyteller did what he claimed). I don't think he did, or it's besides the point, since the main goal seems to be a criticism of the bored, spoiled Red Room members. Oddly reminds me of "The Man Who was Thursday."
